<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-951-744  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 951 744.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Magazine  Feb 14 1989 v8 n3 p56(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>$100 neural network. (Software Review) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Simon, Barry.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>California Scientific Software's Brainmaker, priced at $99.95, isone of several recently released programs providing users with thecapability to build a neural network.andP;  BrainMaker allows the userto choose the representation of input and output as patterns,numbers or symbols, and the number of neurons in the input andoutput layers and one or two hidden layers.andP;  BrainMaker comes witha drop-down menu, a mouse-driven interface and two hefty manuals.andO;BrainMaker is an ideal tool for those wanting to learn more aboutneural network technology.andP;  The program runs under DOS 3.0 andrequires 512K RAM.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   California Scientific Software (products).andO;Product:   BrainMaker (Computer program).andO;Topic:     Neural NetworksSoftware PackagesEvaluation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>$100 Neural Network BrainMaker from California Scientific Software is one ofseveral recently released programs that let you build your own neuralnetworks.andP;  The $99.95 program is an intriguing tool for exploring neuralnets.andM;Neural networks represent the opposite end of the artificial intelligencespectrum from rule-based expert systems.andP;  Rather than formulating a set ofwell-defined rules based on intelligent analysis, neural networks involveforming interconnections in a system based on feedback training.andP;  Once theconnections are right for the trial set, the system has an uncanny knack ofgiving good answers for nearby inputs.andM;With BrainMaker, you choose the representation of input and output aspatterns, numbers, or symbols.andP;  You also choose the number of neurons in theinput and output layers and one or two hidden layers.andP;  BrainMaker also allowsyou to adjust some more-technical parameters.andP;  As you run a set of trialsthrough the network, the connections between the neurons are adjusted via asimple feedback mechanism until the trials are right.andP;  A number of samplenetwork-definition files, which you can see train, are included.andM;BrainMaker comes with a slick drop-down menu, a mouse-driven interface, andtwo thick manuals--one for the program and one on neural networks in general.andO;It is an ideal tool for those interested in learning about this technology.andM;Other new arrivals in the neural network arena include The Brain Simulator($99) from San Francisco-based Abbot, Foster andamp; Hauserman, and NeuroShell($195) from Fredrick, Maryland--based Ward System Group.andO;</TEXT></DOC>